Run the Application Locally with Docker Compose

Follow the steps below to run the application on your local machine.

1. Clone the Repository
git clone <your-repository-url>
cd <repository-folder>
2. Create Environment File

⚠️ Note:
One of the images used in this project is private, so Docker will not be able to pull it unless you have access. If you do not have access, you must build the images locally (see below).

4. Run the Application

Start all services using:

docker compose up -d

This will start:

MySQL Database

Flask Application

The Flask application will be available at:

http://localhost:5000

Alternative: Build Images Locally

If you cannot pull the images (because one image is private), you can build them locally.

Build MySQL Image

Navigate to the MySQL image directory and run:

cd mysql-image-code
docker build -t mysql-with-schema .
Build Flask Application Image

From the application directory:

docker build -t flask-app-image .
Update docker-compose.yml

Update the image names if needed:

image: mysql-with-schema
image: flask-app-image
Run the Application
docker compose up -d
Stop the Application
docker compose down
Remove Containers and Volumes
docker compose down -v
